the fact that we have a clear cut eco-cultural level. People here are divided into two categories; the rich “masters” of the country and the immigrants.

As a young adult trying to express themselves, social life here isn’t the most welcoming one. Being transgender for a long time felt like this alien persona I despised of.

About four or five years ago, as I became more stable mentally and experienced more in life, I also started to accept the fact that this is the reality.

It’s made me definitely a stronger character, a more patient and caring person because I learned to accept my flaws and the flaws of my fellow countrymen.

For people that are experiencing these clashes of who they are and their cultural background, I would advise them to embrace whatever they can from who they are.

Accept that undoubtedly there will be conflicts as times goes by and work them out to find the positives that came out of these events that otherwise would have gone unnoticed.

Do you feel that the type of money you make affects your ability to do more living sateside verses if you stay in your home country?

I wouldn’t say so. What I would say though, is the fact that the economic standards are way better in this part of the world.

Still, from my experience, there’s always something to complain about regardless of your cultural background.

It’s not where you LIVE that matters, but what you DO once you arrived there that affects your quality of life.
